“Lazy Angel” 🕊️ I painted this piece so fast. It was like a whirlwind where I couldn’t paint fast enough.
⠀
I was covering the greens in an old painting with blues. I remember all of the sudden I wanted to paint purple, so I took out this deep purple acrylic ink and drew all over the canvas. Since I was painting so fast, I didn’t have time for it to dry and I smeared the purple into the piece. The rest of the painting was a blur it came together so quickly.
⠀
I love the balance of the painting with the whites. I love the flow of the piece. I love the color palette. I love everything about this painting.
⠀
This piece is special because it reminds me of someone who turned out to be an unexpected angel in my life.
⠀
Thank you, my lazy angel 😇 And by lazy I mean it in that sweet, chill, loving, type B personality, go with the flow type way.
⠀

This was a painting from a visualization. I knew I wanted to start with yellow. I painted some different yellow sections and turned the canvas horizontal. There was a section cut out in the shape of an angel so I painted her in. This is my lazy angel 🕊️😇
⠀
The lazy angel is flying away from the black cave on the bottom right. She is surrounded by different shades of yellow. The sand is next to these bold blue shapes of water. I see some footprints in the sand. There is even some sunshine rain on the left hand side and a yellow tree at the bottom 🌦️☺️
⠀
I hung this painting in my room and I love having all that sunshine ☀️ I don’t typically paint with yellow. It’s not a color I’m drawn to. This painting screams yellow and I love that!!!! ☺️🌼🌝💛🌟
⠀

I made it back home! ☺️ It was a long trip back to Chicago. My flight was delayed six hours, so I downloaded the audio of the new book “The Creative Act” by @rickrubin 👩🏻‍🎨 The book is fantastic! I think a lot of what I do naturally is echoed in his book. He starts with a quote by Robert Henri, "The object isn't to make art, it's to be in that wonderful state that makes art inevitable." I think that beautifully sums up the workshop. Can you be in that place in your work where the paintings just flow? If we focus on enjoying the process, then the paintings will come. I am excited to settle back into my painting routine and see how my work evolves from this experience 🖌️

My collection of three pieces from my trip a few months ago to Santa Fe ☀️ I love this mini series and swipe to see them all!
‌
(1) The Well 🌈—this was the first piece. I remember being so excited and anxious to start painting. This painting feels so free and expressive. It was like everything in me was waiting to come out! I love the boldness of the marks.
‌
(2) Prairie Brook 🤍—the second piece has such a different feel than the first one. I painted the first two pieces next to each other. I was so pleased with all the open space and breathing room in this piece. It has such a beautiful flow and use of neutral colors.
‌
(3) Sunflower 🌻—the last piece and might be my favorite! The studio I was in was called Sunflower so that is how this painting got its name. I love the use of space and how the marks fill the canvas. It has a playful feel with the lines and earth tones.
‌

This is the narrative piece that I did out in Santa Fe. The idea was to use an object or memory as a starting point for a painting. I chose a “get well soon” Winnie the Pooh teddy bear that I had gotten years ago. I wanted to capture the feeling of this stuffed animal. I started with a loose drawing but quickly moved away from that and into the feelings. The Winnie the Pooh is wearing a blue and white striped hospital gown and has a wrapped bandage on its arm and foot. I can see that I was painting those elements along with the orange peach tone of his fur. The dark brown circles I was probably repeating patterns of his nose. I remember putting the green in there and felt like the piece needed it but didn’t know why. Painting is healing for me, and maybe that bandage turned into a rose.

I put it up and I didn’t touch it once. It was perfect. I hope you like it too!
